    <text>
        <body>
            <div>
                <opener><salute>Dear Sir</salute></opener>
                <p>Many thanks for y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
                    <sic>Letter Letter</sic> &amp; acceptable promise of the old map of <placeName ref="pl0813">Breadalbane</placeName>.<note type="editorial">Likely Robert Gordon's
                        'Scotiae provinciae mediterraneae inter Taum flumen et Vararis aestuarium'
                        from Joan Blaeu's <bibl type="editorial"><title ref="bi0093"><hi rend="italic">Atlas Novus</hi></title> (1654)</bibl>.</note> as
                    to <bibl type="authorial"><title ref="bi0209">mine</title></bibl> I think it
                    will never be done so tedious is <persName ref="pe0006">the engraver</persName>.
                    I want much to have <persName ref="pe0155">Lord Seaforthâ€™s</persName>
                    <placeName ref="pl0159">castle Braan</placeName> &amp; the 2 rivers <placeName ref="pl0190">conan</placeName> &amp; Braan<note type="editorial">Possibly a
                        reference to the river called the <placeName ref="pl1905">Black
                            Water</placeName> on modern maps, which joins the Conon above Castle
                        Brahan and may here have been given the name of that residence by Pennant.
                        Pennant's <bibl type="editorial"><title ref="bi0209"><hi rend="italic">Map</hi></title></bibl> of 1777 marks a 'Loch Bran' further up
                        the course of the Conon, though it unclear what geographical feature this
                        corresponds to.</note> set down right, you know the place lies between
                        <placeName ref="pl0191"><unclear reason="illegible">Beaulie</unclear>
                        abby</placeName> &amp; <placeName ref="pl0160">Dingwall</placeName>. Be so
                    good as to get it done &amp; return it. in may I hope to send you a 4<hi rend="superscript">th </hi> vol. of <bibl type="authorial"><title ref="bi0020">Br. Zool.</title></bibl> thanks for y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> designs ab<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>
                    <placeName ref="pl0229">Glasgow</placeName> &amp; <placeName ref="pl0076">Edinburgh</placeName>.</p>
                <closer><salute>I am Dear Sir <lb/>y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> faithful humble
                            Serv<hi rend="superscript">t</hi></salute>
                    <signed><persName ref="pe0232">Tho. Pennant</persName></signed>

                    <dateline><placeName ref="pl0001">Downing</placeName> Dec<hi rend="superscript">r.</hi>
                    31. 1776.</dateline></closer>

                <postscript>
                    <p>you must bind the big plates of the Br. Zool. by themselves according to the
                        numbers in the q<hi rend="superscript">to</hi>.<note type="editorial">This
                            could be a reference either to <rs ref="ar0093">Peter Paillou's
                                plates</rs> for the <bibl type="editorial"><title ref="bi0017">folio
                                    edition of Pennant's <hi rend="italic">British
                                    Zoology</hi></title> (1766)</bibl>, or to enlarged versions of
                            the <rs ref="ar0102">plates</rs> for the <bibl type="editorial"><title ref="bi0019">'Illustrated' British Zoology</title> of
                                1770</bibl>.</note></p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
            <div>
                <p><address>
                        <addrLine>To</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> George Paton</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Custom house</addrLine>
                    </address></p>
            </div>
